Microservices architecture breaks a large application into multiple smaller, independent services.

Each microservice:

* Performs one business function
* Can be deployed independently
* Has its own lifecycle
* Communicates using APIs

For example, an e-commerce application may separate inventory, payments, customer profiles, and shipping into different services.

A real-life use case is airline reservation systems where booking, payment, baggage handling, and notifications operate independently.

Another example is healthcare portals where appointments, billing, and patient records are managed as separate services.

Microservices improve scalability, fault isolation, and development speed.
